<br>
&quot;This contradicts your earlier comments that a skald was comparable damage to a warrior.&quot;<br>
<br>
ROFL. Nothing I said was even related. <br>
<br>
&quot;Your contention seems to be that a skald has greater survivability because minst are a greater threat and therefore skalds survive longer because they aren't targeted to be killed. Well, that's not how rvr works really. it usually goes &quot;easy kill, important kill, tough kill&quot; in that order. Skald falls under easy kill. Minst falls under important/tough, primarily because most classes can't get a grip on them once they have used their RAs or if they are under the influence of Mezz reduction/immunity timers.&quot;<br>
<br>
Wow. Well I have to say your understanding of RvR and priorities is a bit out of whack. First off, a good player in RvR will understand that there are three classifications of targets: Priority or Important targets (Any caster, any healer), rogues and tanks. Priority targets are not killed first because they are the easiest to kill, although that is a factor. They are killed first because left unchecked they can singlehandedly destroy a group. Minstrels are in a different boat because of SoS. If they are mezzed and not purging, they are lower priority than any healer or caster. If they are unmezzed they are very high priority. Skalds are very low priority because they are a hybrid tank and not as easy to take down as any caster and tougher to take down than a healer (only because if you are on a skald rather than a healer, you have a healer free to heal the skald, while if on a healer, you have one less person distributing heals. <br>
<br>
&quot;for the record i have a RR6l4 Skald and partial ownership of a rr8l2 minst.&quot; <br>
<br>
WOW PARTIAL OWENERSHIP? Whooptidoo....<br>
<br>
&quot;So i've seen it from both sides and i can guarentee you my minst lives far longer then my skald 99% of the time, primarily because i can do my job without being right in the front line area, which is not feasible for a skald to be effective, they must wade in.&quot;<br>
<br>
A minstrel will live longer against retards, but that is all I will give you. Since alot of the people, surprisingly enough, are not COMPLETE morons, I am usually among the last to die. Even some of the worst groups have decent target selection. My group gets rid of minstrels fairly quickly.<br>
<br>
&quot;A minst can maintain a 1000 unit buffer to most of the dangerous combat while at the same time reducing the ranged threat to them while on the move (mezz and kite). Mezz may not stick after the inital cast, but it DOES interrupt, and thats all you need to survive a ranged caster and interrupt healers at a distance, just run around and spam cast it on them, you've done your entire team an invaluable service while maintaining a posture that allows you to live through most if not all fights.&quot;<br>
<br>
It is decent useful as an interrupt, but if you have a decent sorcerer in your group and you are using your mez, you are doing your group a disservice. Nothing changes a battle more than having a cleric or friar rez a sorcerer mid-battle and having the sorcerer get off another mez. A minstrel that is giving everyone immunity timers would piss me off if I were a sorcerer. In fact when I was a newbie minstrel I got chewed out by one of the better sorcerers I have met for doing the exact thing you are trying to convince me is the way to play a minstrel. Anyway, it is useful if your sorcerer sucks, but otherwise isn't a big help.<br>
<br>
&quot;To say the AE mezz is inconsequential is horribly inaccurate, a well played minst can lock down entire armies of ranged attackers with it and cause healers a constant headache.&quot;<br>
<br>
A Minstrel standing in one place and spamming the 5 second cast AE mez is a newbie minstrel and makes me laugh IRL.<br>
<br>
&quot;Skald has 1 timered range interrupt at 1500 units, other then that they have to close to a min. 700 to continue to interrupt casters, then its a timer.&quot;<br>
<br>
A good Skald spaces out his interrupts s othat one is always up. Guess that isn't something you have figured out yet. No problem, you will learn.<br>
<br>
&quot;Minst are designed to be survivable support classes, tho it may be true that skalds and minst both die a lot in close combat with heavy tanks, a minst has the optiont to do his job without being in that situation where a skald doesn't.&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, you have somewhat of a point, but again, I would argue that a minstrel in a good group with a good sorc is better served using his DDs and stun to interrupt and helping tanks on an /assisted target.<br>
<br>
&quot;Your selective use of stun is your choice, however that doesn't mean that other uses for it don't make it a very powerful tool, for instance using Stun on Pbaer who is about to nail your CCed realmmates can save them a substantial amount of damage.&quot; <br>
<br>
I never disqualified using stun in such a way. However, skald mez is superior to stun in that situation. If he MOC's stun won't last long enough. In any case, I don't usually run into problems with pbaers. They are generally dead or mezzed before we have problems with them. Guess we are coming from different perspectives here. =)<br>
<br>
&quot;there are quite a fewer other uses for stun, to be honest, your better off using mezz on the move to stop most runners (except those with immunity) because then when you close to combat and engage, you can stun mid combat with no timer concern if the fight becomes too tough.&quot;<br>
<br>
Stun is better in my opinion if you have a good caster in your group that pays attention and can take out the runner without much effort.<br>
<br>
&quot;This would be true if the snare didn't break upon next damage to the target.&quot;<br>
<br>
Mez breakd on damage too. Don't see your point here pal.<br>
<br>
&quot;very very rarely when you are chasing somebody through an active battle field will you land a snare that really sticks for more then a couple of seconds with the tons of AE being thrown around and people trying to take a shot at the target as its running past.&quot;<br>
<br>
Unless I am around a bunch of other groups, we don't really use AEs and people generally are not all on different targets. I guess I am used to more discipline than that. When surrounded by people that know what they are doing the snare is very very usefuk.<br>
<br>
&quot;Additionally, bleed styles, dots and some pulsing effects can break snare.&quot;<br>
<br>
For many purposes the snare only needs to interrupt or snare the person for a few seconds. Long duration snare isnt' what makes it great. It is the fact that it is a shout, has good range and lasts a decent amount of time. Even if it breaks, I have several extra seconds to catch them. <br>
<br>
&quot;Once you've snared and had it broken, you've given the target in question root immunity, which means should they get away from you (like say you get cced or otherwise stopped) the next caster they go after has no CC option to stop them unless they try to mezz (sm)&quot;<br>
<br>
Again different perspectives here I guess. Root immunity is a problem with the snare, but in a good group everyone has to rely on cross-ccing. I don't find it to be a problem and our shammy, who is largely responsible for rooting people off casters hasn't complained. I think it is really a matter of experience and being selective in your use of it. A lot of people, yourself included I imagine, probably spam snare for the sole purpose of interrupting as soon as the timer is up. Well, with selective use of snare, it can be so much more. I do my best not to use it JUST for interrupts except in emergencies.<br>
<br>
&quot;From a skill set perspective, skald snare is incredibly inferior to prevent flight, both in its casted form and its styled form.&quot;<br>
<br>
LOL!! What does that have to do with the discussion? Prevent Flight is a great ability. So? The fact that prevent Flight exists doesnt' have a bearing on whether Skalds are a good class or not.<br>
<br>
&quot;A low stealth high weapon/instrument minst is very very capable of taking down people in 1 round of combat (casters)&quot;<br>
<br>
Bull. Absolute bull. You show me a caster that goes down from 350ish dmg in shouts and &gt;200 melee dmg and I show you a level 40 caster. God, don't be an idiot.<br>
<br>
&quot;Minst and skald are on identical weaponskill tables, the myth that skalds have higher weaponskill was perpetuated by people comparing low str minst chars to Trolls skalds. it's simply not true.&quot;<br>
<br>
Talking out of your ass here buddy. You can't show me any documentation on this at all. I wouldn't doubt it, but again, you are making it up.<br>
<br>
&quot;A minst with an Anchor (slow 1 hand weapon) will do very good damage per strike vs cloth casters, add in their DDs and mastery of pain II (aug str one helps also) and they can approach close to 430 with an opening blow + 300 from DDs, that's enough to take out an unbuffed caster.&quot;<br>
<br>
Rofl. 430? If they have like 0 melee or body resists AND if you are buffed AND if you crit AND if they aren't buffed. Sounds like a LOT has to go right for that to happen. In reality you will never take down a level 50 caster with decent gear in one round of combat even if you are buffed and they aren't. You are dwelling into the realm of the ridiculous here. Get back to reality. People run buffed and almost always have capped resists. If they don't, they aren't really worth using as an example of RvR prowess.<br>
<br>
&quot;Should they perfect crit on the attack or get a positional off, that damage goes up quite a bit.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Plus they can stun said caster and beat on them a couple more times with the positional of their choice without worrying about the first shot breaking their mezz and the caster qc ccing them or lifetapping them.&quot;<br>
<br>
Uh huh. Again. A minstrel will never kill as fast as an equally skilled or equipped Skald. Never. My minstrel had the best gear in the game and never came close to the 500+ NON CRIT attacks I issue out to casters regularly on my skald.<br>
<br>
&quot;Wish i had my other computer up, i'd throw up the screenie of minst hitting mana eld for 419, 189 139 (dds) then hitting for 560. The mana eld lived because he got an insta from his druid. Clearly there is a crit in there (mana eld took shot), but the point is, minst can do = damage to skald if they low spec stealth, which they don't NEED in rvr. Skald can only spec for max damage if they gimp their BS song a bit.&quot;<br>
<br>
Lol. You are desribing an ideal situation. That is a once in a lifetime hit for a minstrel. Two obvious crits. I sincerely doubt that caster had capped resists. SINCERELY. Post the screenie though I would love to see that because I think you are fibbing. =p In any case, you are posting your most ideal situation wheras that is normal to see from a good Skald. That is the difference, your best example of minstrel pwnage is like average for my skald. As for gimping BS line for max damage, I used to be 50 Sword spec and hit for 700+ routinely on casters. However, I do much more average damage now as a 50 BS Skald than I ever did as 50 Sword. You don't know what you are talking about here guy.<br>
<br>
&quot;Refer to my comment about tying up everyone in the back areas with chain mezzes. compare how many people a skald can tie up compared to a minst then.&quot;<br>
<br>
I suppose a Minstrel can &quot;tie up&quot; more people than a Skald, but this isn't a debate about how well Skalds CC versus Minstrels. I said they had better survivability. You made it into a minstrel versus skald debate. Anyway, while the minstrel is back their &quot;tying people up&quot; a Skald is inflicting damage. It is my believe after playing both classes (and not pretending someone else's minstrel is mine) that it is more benficial to have some CC, a lot of damage than a lot of gimpy CC and subpar damage. <br>
<br>
a minst + Pally interaction is greater then any duo in mid.<br>
